The article discusses the White House's plans for middle class economics in the 21st century. The main goals are to raise wages and incomes, strengthen the standing of working families, and provide support for healthcare, child care, housing, and retirement. The article outlines several specific proposals, such as eliminating the trust fund loophole, cutting taxes for working families, increasing the minimum wage, and making a home more affordable. Other proposals include making two years of community college free, reducing student loan debt, expanding on-the-job training opportunities, fixing the business tax code, promoting American jobs and workers, investing in R&D and clean energy, simplifying tax filing for small businesses, and reforming the criminal justice system. The article also discusses the administration's plans for immigration reform, building trust between communities and law enforcement, combating climate change, serving veterans, safeguarding consumers in the digital age, and making government more efficient.